<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#F0DCA0">Originally posted by lenni on 11-15-1999 11:19 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Hi, LAR !

I do not write very often in this forum but I`m a great fan of you and your work ! So, I don`t hope that PROJECT C will not have the same destiny like LMK !!!!    We`ll see.
Now to your question: the AI !

For me it`s very important that each character is able to act in different ways. 
One example: my party is in a dungeon, there is a locked door, the party opens the door and see 3 ugly goblins sitting around a table. What happens now- first, 2 goblins taking their bows and try to shoot us, the third goblin blocked  the way in order to keep us in distance.
Maybe there is another reaction of the three goblins. Second, two of them are fighting against us and the third is fleeing... – third, it depends on how the party opens the door. Do they surprise the group of goblins or do they only stumble in the room. I think you know what I mean.
What I hate is when you meet some people in a friendly town you speak to them and a window is opening with three different choices of conversation. And each time you meet the same or other inhabitans of the town you often get the same three choices. I think there is no individualtiy. 
Thats all for the moment, I think it`s very hard to discuss AI on this way because you must write romans.
But there is one thing I would like to say: for me is the most important thing in a roleplaygame that there is a good, a very good story and a charcter or a group of characters of whom you can identify with !!!! 
Well we will see what you do....

Lenni
</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
